    {
      "_id": "MPParagraphElement:F280955D-2F6A-488E-A488-7DED4893E41E",
      "contents": "<p xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\" id=\"MPParagraphElement:F280955D-2F6A-488E-A488-7DED4893E41E\" class=\"MPElement\" data-object-type=\"MPParagraphElement\">Lung cancers are broadly divided into non-small-cell lung cancer (NSCLC) and small-cell lung cancer (SCLC) [<span class=\"citation\" data-reference-id=\"MPCitation:6825B192-B3CF-4465-8D17-9115EE1BC793\">4</span>]. About 80%–85% of lung cancers are NSCLC, and 10%–15% of all lung cancers are SCLC. The survival rate of lung cancer is low. In 2008, there were 12.7 million cancer cases and 7.6 million cancer deaths, with 56% of patients and 64% of fatalities occurring in economically developing countries. Lung cancer is the most common cancer site in men, accounting for 17% of all new cancer cases and 23% of cancer deaths [<span class=\"citation\" data-reference-id=\"MPCitation:EA0B238D-A943-4865-AA3D-35F21D6ACD5B\">5</span>]. Lung cancer is diagnosed at an advanced stage in approximately 70% of patients, with a 5-year survival rate of approximately 16%. However, if lung cancer is detected early, it has a better chance of being treated successfully, with a 5-year survival rate of 70% [<span class=\"citation\" data-reference-id=\"MPCitation:EC5888AE-1524-4000-869C-2B92E98F88BE\">6</span>, <span class=\"citation\" data-reference-id=\"MPCitation:66756171-D450-45DF-ADFC-B608412F3D91\">7</span>]. One of the leading causes of lung cancer is smoking. It can even happen to those who have never smoked. It can be increased by exposure to secondhand smoking, arsenic, asbestos, radioactive dust, or radon.</p>",
