      "_id": "MPParagraphElement:A201EC21-AB10-4E9E-A134-3F3D78C61888",
      "contents": "<p xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\" id=\"MPParagraphElement:A201EC21-AB10-4E9E-A134-3F3D78C61888\" class=\"MPElement\" data-object-type=\"MPParagraphElement\">Lung nodule segmentation is a crucial process designed to make the quantitative assessment of clinical criteria such as size, shape, location, density, texture, and the CAD system more manageable and more efficient [<span class=\"citation\" data-reference-id=\"MPCitation:FDC411BE-5D4C-48D2-912E-4E7380EE69A1\">196</span>–<span class=\"citation\" data-reference-id=\"MPCitation:823DD535-B360-42E9-8832-A2DCA318A435\">198</span>]. However, because of their solidity, location, or texture, lung nodules such as juxta-pleural (nodules directly attached to the pleura’s surface), juxta-vascular (nodules connected to vessels), and ground-glass nodules can be challenging to remove. Deep learning-based segmentation is a pixel-by-pixel categorization technique used to calculate organ probability [<span class=\"citation\" data-reference-id=\"MPCitation:B3ECB003-404C-4423-BF10-0E6772A84917\">30</span>]. This method is divided into two stages: the first is the creation of the probability map using CNN and image patches and the second is the refinement of the probability map using the general background of images and the probability map [<span class=\"citation\" data-reference-id=\"MPCitation:1CDA2D34-C31E-4860-8041-5CBF3A2739FF\">196</span>].</p>",
