      "_id": "MPParagraphElement:44F5EE75-9962-4ECE-B52D-2176E7FE1710",
      "contents": "<p xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\" id=\"MPParagraphElement:44F5EE75-9962-4ECE-B52D-2176E7FE1710\" class=\"MPElement\" data-object-type=\"MPParagraphElement\">Wavelet is a frequency selecting handling [<span class=\"citation\" data-reference-id=\"MPCitation:F02F040A-ECA7-44FC-953C-76C8334F4EE5\">263</span>]. The wavelet change can assist with changing over the sign into a structure that makes it a lot simpler for our pinnacle locator work. Sometime after the first ECG signal, the wave coefficient for each scale is plotted. Wavelet was used by Arulmurugan et al.[<span class=\"citation\" data-reference-id=\"MPCitation:9BF5360A-199A-44A2-8DFC-184207519EEE\">22</span>] to extract features. Soufi et al. [<span class=\"citation\" data-reference-id=\"MPCitation:49B756D2-3D2C-4A4A-A6FB-2F9D9411BEFE\">264</span>] attempted to detect lung cancer using a wavelet. Park et al. [<span class=\"citation\" data-reference-id=\"MPCitation:444C3A1D-9A78-424D-AE61-8C395CCA1C29\">265</span>] included and extracted a large number of wavelet features. A discrete wavelet transform (DWT) is a signal decomposition into number sets. Every set is a period series of coefficients portraying the time development of the signal in the corresponding frequency band (DWT). DWT is an effective tool for multiresolution analysis, and it is primarily pursued in signal processing, image analysis, and various classification systems [<span class=\"citation\" data-reference-id=\"MPCitation:718861A4-B479-433E-9AA2-0148C1BA2BDF\">266</span>]. It is broadly used in feature extraction as it is efficient, which can be declared by seeing its previous results.</p>",
