    {
      "_id": "MPParagraphElement:706E6AE6-9F61-4E4E-8D0B-4FDF28BE63CB",
      "contents": "<p xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\" id=\"MPParagraphElement:706E6AE6-9F61-4E4E-8D0B-4FDF28BE63CB\" class=\"MPElement\" data-object-type=\"MPParagraphElement\">Recall/sensitivity is the number of pertinent records recovered by a search isolated by existing significant archives. Sensitivity is another name for recall. The test’s sensitivity reflects the likelihood that the screening test will be positive among unhealthy people. The number of applicable archives recovered is referred to as recall. It computes the number of true positives detected by the model and marks them as positives [<span class=\"citation\" data-reference-id=\"null\">352</span>]. Finally, it estimates the capacity of a test to be positive when the condition is present. It is otherwise called false negative rate, review, Type II error, <i>β</i> error, error or oversight, or elective theory [<span class=\"citation\" data-reference-id=\"MPCitation:A56B4DC9-E8BE-4053-9F55-A0ABDDE9F44F\">69</span>].</p>",
      "createdAt": 1694167156,
      "updatedAt": 1694167156,
      "objectType": "MPParagraphElement",
      "containerID": "MPProject:c4855a02-050a-452c-af9d-3a2e4501a96e",
