      "_id": "MPParagraphElement:84BA5062-F095-40CD-8F60-017C1C036736",
      "contents": "<p xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\" id=\"MPParagraphElement:84BA5062-F095-40CD-8F60-017C1C036736\" class=\"MPElement\" data-object-type=\"MPParagraphElement\">Specificity is the capacity of a test to distinguish individuals without illness effectively. The test’s specificity reflects the likelihood that the screening test will be negative among people who do not have the illness. It estimates a test’s ability to be harmful when the condition is not present. It is otherwise called FP rate, precision, Type I error, <i>α</i> error, error of commission, or null hypothesis [<span class=\"citation\" data-reference-id=\"MPCitation:F9D27896-8E86-4E18-9B95-E4B4BB2734D2\">278</span>].</p>",
